Column Comment.0: ANALYSIS IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for a sample analysis. Various types ofanalysis may be conducted on a sample. Samples may be derived from lithologiccuttings, fluid collection etc.
Column Comment.1: ANALYSIS SOURCE: The source that the analysis came from, this could be a labtechnician, a lab, a company, a government agency, etc.
Column Comment.2: MEASUREMENT OBSERVATION NUMBER: A unique observation number for themeasurement in the maceral analysis.
Column Comment.3: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y or N flag indicating whether this row of data is currentlyeither active/valid (Y) or inactive/invalid (N).
Column Comment.4: COAL RANK IDENTIFIER: A unique identifier for the coal rank of the coal.
Column Comment.5: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.6: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.7: FLUORESENCE COLOR: The color of the fluorescence being used in the analysis ofthe alteration of the sediment.
Column Comment.8: FLUORESENCE INTENSITY DESCRIPTION: A narrative description of the intensityof the fluorescence being used in the analysis of the alteration of the sediment.
Column Comment.9: FLUORESENCE INTENSITY VALUE: The value of the intensity of the fluorescence.
Column Comment.11: MEAN MAXIMUM REFLECTANCE: The mean maximum reflectance of themeasured light.
Column Comment.12: MEAN RANDOM REFLECTANCE: The mean random reflectance of the measuredlight.
Column Comment.13: MEASUREMENTS COUNT: A number count of the of the measurements taken in themaceral analysis.
Column Comment.14: POPULATION NAME: The name of the population.
Column Comment.15: POPULATION NUMBER: The number of the population.
Column Comment.16: POPULATION OBSERVATION NUMBER: A unique observation number for thepopulation.
Column Comment.17: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should becreated.
Column Comment.18: PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating that the sample is matured to theright age.
Column Comment.19: PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is a problem withthe step. If a yes flag is indicated, additional information regarding the problemshould be noted in the table ANL_PROBLEM.
Column Comment.20: REFLECTED MAXIMUM MEASURED VALUE: The maximum measured value of thereflected light.
Column Comment.23: REFLECTED MEASURED VALUE: The value of the measured reflected light.
Column Comment.26: REFLECTED MINIMUM MEASURED VALUE: The minimum measured value of thereflected light.
Column Comment.29: REFLECTED STANDARD DEVIATION VALUE: The value of the standard deviationof the reflected light.
Column Comment.30: REFLECTED RANDOM MEASURED VALUE: The value of the random reflected lightmeasured.;
Column Comment.33: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.34: REWORKED PERCENT: The percentage of reworked material in the maceralsample. Reworked material is out-of-place sediment from a time perspective. Thismaterial can be out-of-place due to heavy rain fall, tectonic action, or any geologicevent that could have enough impact to move the sediment. The percentage ofreworked material is important in that it can enable one to uncover events that mayhave occurred during a certain time period.
Column Comment.35: SAMPLE TOTAL MACERAL VALUE: The total value of the maceral sample.
Column Comment.37: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.38: STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique number indicating the sequence of the stepamong other steps in the preparation and processing of the sample.
Column Comment.39: SUBSTANCE IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for a substance that can be describedeither chemically or in terms of composition. Elements, ions, isotopes, isomers,minerals, chemicals, solvents, production substances, hydrocarbons etc are all listed.Be advised that many applications and agencies may use the same term, but thedefinition and composition details may not be the same. Use the SUBSTANCE XREFtable to capture relationships between substances, such as similar substances.
Column Comment.40: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.41: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.42: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.43: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.44: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.45: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.46: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
